A health professional holds a swab test for the COVID-19 coronavirus at a drive-through testing site outside the Lancet Laboratories facilities in Johannesburg. JOHANNESBURG - Health Minister Zweli Mkhize has warned South Africans to brace for an increase in the number of COVID-19 cases, even during the lockdown. The number of confirmed infections rose to 709 on Wednesday. READ: COVID-19 cases in SA climb to 709 Two patients are currently in ICU in private hospitals. Three doctors -- one in Limpopo, Mpumalanga and the Free State -- have tested positive. READ: Lockdown shopping: Commission concerned over price hikes Mkhize said there are no fatalities and that all patients are improving. He said the largest number of scattered cases are in Johannesburg. In the Western Cape, scattered cases are around Cape Town. READ: COVID-19: 21-days lockdown explained Mkhize says the health department will increase testing facilities, but there will be strict criteria as to who can get tested. "We test those with a history of symptoms and a history of contact and travel," he said. Mkhize urged South Africans to abide to the lockdown rules, social distancing and hygienic measures. Coronavirus Hotline Number: 0800 029 999 from 8am to 4pm, Monday to Friday Help protect your loved ones by sharing this official South African government COVID-19 service with your family, friends and community. Send HI to 0600 123 456 on WhatsApp. The NICD has another Clinician Hotline to improve #COVID19 communication and support for healthcare providers. The Clinician Hotline is 0800 11 1131, operating 24 hrs. The Public Hotline is 0800 029 999 also operating 24hrs.